<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-654-726  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 654 726.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>IEEE Spectrum  July 1990 v27 n7 p40(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Toward more compatible human-computer interfaces.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Nickerson, Raymond S.; Pew, Richard W.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The need to improve human-computer interfaces becomes morecritical as more people use microcomputers.andP;  Human factors is animportant factor in designing a successful interface.andP;  The designshould be an interactive design, which leaves some design optionsopen so features and functions can be added after the designersees how the user reacts.andP;  There are two kinds of activities thataid this process: task analysis where the designer has a detailedunderstanding of the tasks to be performed and how the userperforms them and rapid prototyping where software tools simulatesome of all features of an actual interface.andP;  Evaluation of aproduct design is done as the product evolves with results fedback into the design.andP;  The interface design should make itdifficult to do something disastrous inadvertently; give the userthe feeling of manipulating directly the entities of interestinstead of the system doing it; have modules of applications forusers tasks; use simple metaphors; permit interactive access onlywhen needed; and help the user navigate through the informationprovided.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Human FactorsUser InterfaceSoftware EngineeringSystems AnalysisSystem Design.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Some basic human factors design principles. (table)Evaluation of three rapid-prototyping tools for large systems.andO;(table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>